result.execSummary:
The defendant Daniel F Dye was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant in person & by Atty. Jeffrey William Jensen.  Atty. Mandy A. Schepper appeared for State.  Record opened:  8:39 a.m.  Discussion between Court and counsel regarding prior convictions; Court will allow one conviction to be stated to the jury.  Case called;  8:54 a.m.  Same appearances.  Jury panel present and sworn; 20 jurors called to the box.  Voir dire by Court and counsel.  Counsel exercise strikes, 12 juror names called.  Court thanks balance of panel and excuses them from this trial.  Jury sworn.  Jury not present.  Defense moves for sequestration of witnesses and Court so orders with exemption of Deputy Vandlen.  Jury present.  Opening statements by counsel.  WITNESS:  Andrew M.; Deputy Bryon Vandlen (WCSD).  Jury not present.  Court addresses concerns of counsel regarding behavior of witnesses during break.  Court admonishes witnesses.  Jury present.  WITNESS:  Deputy Bryon Vandlen (WCSD).  Court admonishes and releases jury for lunch.  Recess.  Reconvene.  WITNESS:  Deputy Bryon Vandlen (WCSD).  State rests.  Defense motions to dismiss.  WITNESS:  Paul B.  Jury not present.  Court has colloquy with Defendant regarding his right to testify.  Jury present.  WITNESS:  Daniel D.  REBUTTAL WITNESS:  Deputy Bryon Vandlen (WCSD).  Jury not present.  Argument on defense motion to dismiss disorderly conduct charge.  Court denies motion to dismiss.  Recess.  Reconvene.  Jury not present.  Finalize jury instructions and verdicts.  Jury present.  Court instructs jury.  Closing statements by counsel.  Bailiff sworn.  Jury exits for deliberations at 3:49 p.m.  Jury returns with verdict at 5:21 p.m.  Jury Foreperson:  Juror #1850.  Court reads the verdicts as follows:  guilty on Ct. 1; guilty on Ct. 2.  Jury polled.   State moves for judgment on the verdicts.  Court enters judgment on the verdicts.  Defendant wishes to proceed to sentencing today.  Argument by counsel.  Statement by Defendant.  Court proceeds to sentencing.
